Source: Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report, West Nile Virus
Activity Weekly Update, Fri 26 Oct 2001 / 50(42);26-7,[edited
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5042a4.htm>

West Nile Virus Activity - United States: 17 to 23 Oct 2001
-----------------------------------------------------------
The following report summarizes West Nile virus (WNV) surveillance
data reported to CDC through ArboNET and verified by states and other
jurisdictions as of Tue 23 Oct 2001.
During the week of 17 to 23 Oct 2001, 6 human cases of WNV
encephalitis or meningitis were reported in Pennsylvania (3), New
Jersey (2), and Florida (1). During the same period, WNV infections
were reported in 101 crows, 45 other birds, and 26 horses. A total of
31 WNV-positive mosquito pools were reported in 5 states (Connecticut,
Florida, Georgia, New York, and Ohio).
Cumulative totals
---------------------
Human
--------
During 2001, 37* human cases of WNV encephalitis or meningitis have
been reported in Florida (10), Maryland (6), New York (6), New Jersey
(6), Connecticut (5), Pennsylvania (3), and Georgia (1); one death
occurred in Georgia. Among these 37 cases, 20 (54%) were in males, the
median age was 69 years (range: 36 to 81 years), and dates of illness
onset ranged from 13 Jul - 7 Oct 2001.
Horses
---------
[The MMWR Update is still under-reporting the number of confirmed
equine cases. The USDA-APHIS update of Mon 15 Oct 2001 (see: West Nile
virus surveillance 2001 - USA (26) ref. above) identifies 191
confirmed equine cases distributed through 15 states. - Mod.CP.
Birds
------
3796 crows and 1394 other birds with WNV infection were reported from
25 states and the District of Columbia; 151 WNV infections in other
animals (all horses) were reported from 11 states (Alabama,
Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Massachusetts,
Mississippi, New York, Pennsylvania, and Virginia); and
Mosquitoes
--------------
725 WNV-positive mosquito pools were reported from 14 states
(Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Kentucky, Maryland,
Massachusetts, Michigan, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, and Rhode Island).
Additional information about WNV activity is available at
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/westnile/index.htm>
&
<http://cindi.usgs.gov/hazard/event/west_nile/west_nile.html>.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
*[The first human case of WNV infection in Louisiana was reported on
Tue 23 Oct 2001, bringing the total of human cases in 2001 to 38 (see:
West Nile virus, human - USA (Louisiana) 20011023.2617). - Mod.CP
